        output='# SpaceX S-1 Space Segment Revenue Breakdown — Detailed Findings\n\n## (1) Launch Services vs. Launch & Development — What\'s Included\n\nThe S-1 draws a clear distinction between the two Space sub-segments:\n\n**Launch Services:**\n> "Launch Services for the deployment of payloads to their intended orbits for both commercial and government customers utilizing Falcon 9 and Falcon Heavy."\n\n- Derived from **fixed-price contracts ranging from one to five years**\n- Revenue recognized **at a point in time** — specifically "upon the launch or deployment of the customer\'s payload to their intended orbit"\n- Rationale: "due to the interchangeability of flight hardware and minimal unique engineering costs"\n- Revenue and costs are **deferred** until launch/deployment\n\n**Launch & Development:**\n> "Launch and Development for the development of spacecraft and provision of launch and mission services for government agency space programs utilizing Falcon 9, Falcon Heavy, Starship, and Dragon."\n\n- Derived from **fixed-price contracts ranging from one to fourteen years** (notably longer duration)\n- Revenue recognized **over time** using the **cost-to-cost input method**\n- Recognition condition: "the Company\'s performance on the contract creates an asset with no alternative use and the Company has an enforceable right to payment for performance to date"\n- Notably includes **Starship and Dragon** — vehicles not mentioned in Launch Services\n- Predominantly **government agency** space programs\n\nThe MD&A explicitly states the expectation that Launch & Development will grow as a share of Space revenue:\n> "We expect Launch and Development to represent a larger portion of our Space revenue as we continue to serve our long-term contracts for our government customers."\n\nThe percentage mix table shows Launch & Development rising from 31.8% (2024) → 37.0% (2025) → 46.7% (Q1 2026), confirming this trajectory.\n\n---\n\n## (2) Per-Launch Revenue / Average Revenue per Launch\n\nThe S-1 **references** the concept but **does not disclose a specific dollar figure** for average revenue per launch. The only direct mention is:\n\n> "While total Falcon launches increased by 31 from 134 in 2024 to 165 in 2025, Space customer launches and average price per launch remained relatively flat year over year."\n\nOne can **derive an implied figure** from the disaggregated revenue table and launch counts, but the filing itself does not state it. Using the disclosed data:\n\n| Period | Launch Services Revenue | Total Falcon Launches | Customer Launches (implied) |\n|--------|------------------------|-----------------------|------------------------------|\n| 2024 | $2,584M | 134 | Not separately disclosed |\n| 2025 | $2,576M | 165 | "remained relatively flat" |\n\nThe filing notes that total Falcon launches include internal Starlink deployments, so dividing Launch Services revenue by total Falcon launches would **overstate** the denominator. The S-1 does not provide a clean customer-launch count that would allow precise per-launch calculation.\n\n---\n\n## (3) External Customer Launches vs. Internal Starlink Launches — Separate Disclosure\n\n**Yes, the S-1 explicitly separates these**, though the treatment is asymmetric:\n\n**External customer launches → recognized as Space segment revenue:**\n> "Our Space segment revenue only reflects our customer launches and customer activities."\n\n**Internal Starlink launches → NO inter-segment revenue recognized:**\n> "For launches of our Starlink satellites, the Company does not recognize any inter-segment revenue, rather those launch costs are capitalized in satellites in Property, plant, and equipment, net."\n\n> "For launches dedicated to deploying our Starlink satellites, we capitalize the associated costs within our Connectivity segment and depreciate them over time, and we do not recognize revenue for those launches in our Space segment."\n\nThe filing also explains the operational dynamic that creates period-to-period volatility:\n> "When an expected customer payload for a planned launch is not available, we instead use launch capacity for our satellites. As a result, we adjust expected launch payloads frequently, impacting period-to-period financial comparison."\n\nAnd it quantifies the cost capitalization impact:\n> "...the relative increase in Starlink satellite launches from 63 launches in 2023 to 89 launches in 2024, resulting in relatively more of our launch operations and overhead costs capitalized in our Connectivity segment of $99 million."\n\nThe S-1 also flags future capacity reallocation to a third internal use:\n> "We allocate a significant amount of launch capacity to our Connectivity segment, and expect to allocate a significant amount to our AI segment in the future."\n\nHowever, the filing does **not** provide a standalone line item showing the **count** of customer launches vs. internal Starlink launches in a given period. It discloses total Falcon launches (e.g., 134 in 2024, 165 in 2025) and Starlink launch counts (63 in 2023, 89 in 2024), but does not present these in a single reconciling table.\n\n---\n\n## (4) Definition of "Flight-Proven Booster Launches" and "Booster Launches" KPIs\n\nThe S-1 provides a **full definition of "Launches"** as a KPI but **does not provide an explicit standalone definition** of "flight-proven booster launches" or "booster launches" as separately named KPIs. Here is what the filing does state:\n\n**Definition of "Launches" (the primary KPI):**\n> "Launches are a key measure of our operational scale, which in turn supports our revenue growth and mission to expand humanity\'s presence in space. Launches in a period represent the sum of all successful orbital and flight tests across our rockets, including internal Starlink deployments, development tests, and launches for our third-party customers, and excluding any cancellations or scrubs that occurred in that period."\n\n**What "booster" means (structural definition):**\n> "The Company\'s Falcon 9 and Falcon Heavy are composed of boosters (also known as first stages), second stages, Merlin engines, and fairings. Boosters, fairings, and Merlin engines are reusable and are classified as property, plant, [and equipment]."\n\n**Usage of "flight-proven booster launches" in context:**\n> "During the three months ended March 31, 2026, we launched 40 Falcon rockets, of which 39 were flight-proven booster launches, and in 2025, we launched 165 Falcon 9 rockets, of which 157 were flight-proven booster launches."\n\n**Inferred meaning:** Based on the structural definition (boosters = first stages, which are reusable), "flight-proven booster launches" refers to missions that used a **previously flown (recovered and refurbished) first-stage booster** rather than an expendable or first-flight booster. The term "flight-proven" is industry-standard language for hardware that has completed at least one prior mission. The very high ratio (39/40 in Q1 2026; 157/165 in 2025) underscores the degree of reusability achieved.\n\n**Important caveat:** The S-1 does **not** include a formal glossary entry or defined-term definition for "flight-proven booster launches" or "booster launches" in the provided chunks. The defined-terms section covers "Space segment," "SpaceX Bridge Loan," "SpaceX Credit Facility," "spectrum," "Starlink," and "Starlink Consumer Broadband" — but not the launch-related KPIs. The meaning must therefore be inferred from context and the structural description of Falcon vehicles.\n\n---\n\n## Summary of Gaps\n\n| Question | Answered? | Notes |\n|----------|-----------|-------|\n| Launch Services vs. L&D composition | ✅ Yes | Clearly defined with vehicle types, contract durations, and recognition methods |\n| Per-launch revenue figure | ⚠️ Partial | Concept referenced ("average price per launch remained relatively flat") but no dollar amount disclosed |\n| Customer vs. internal launch revenue separation | ✅ Yes | Explicitly stated: customer launches = Space revenue; Starlink launches = capitalized, no revenue |\n| Flight-proven booster launches definition | ⚠️ Partial | "Launches" KPI is formally defined; "flight-proven booster launches" is used but not formally defined as a separate KPI |',
        error=None,
