economics (the reusability + vertical integration signal):** The more revealing comparison is per-kilogram. SpaceX\'s implied ~$2,630/kg is roughly **one-eleventh** of Rocket Lab\'s ~$28,300/kg. This dramatic gap is the economic signature of two structural advantages:\n\n1. **Vehicle reusability:** In 2025, 157 of 165 Falcon 9 launches (95.2%) used flight-proven (previously flown and recovered) first-stage boosters. This collapses the marginal hardware cost per launch toward second-stage + fairing + propellant + operations, rather than a full new vehicle. Rocket Lab\'s Electron is predominantly expendable, so each launch consumes a complete new vehicle — its disclosed cost per launch ($4.8M in 2025) is ~56% of its revenue per launch, leaving limited margin headroom. SpaceX does not disclose cost per launch, but the 95% booster-reuse rate implies a structurally lower marginal cost ratio.\n\n2. **Vertical integration:** SpaceX manufactures its Merlin engines, avionics, structures, and fairings in-house, capturing the full launch value chain and avoiding supplier margins. Rocket Lab is also vertically integrated (it builds its own Rutherford engines and much of Electron), but at far smaller scale, limiting unit-cost amortization. SpaceX\'s vertical integration compounds with reusability: in-house recovery, refurbishment, and reflight of boosters/fairings is only economically viable because SpaceX controls the hardware design and manufacturing.\n\n**Directional takeaway:** The comparison shows that reusability and vertical integration do **not** reduce SpaceX\'s *revenue* per launch (which remains high in absolute terms because the vehicle is large) — rather, they compress the *cost* per launch and per kilogram, allowing SpaceX to pass through lower per-kg pricing to customers while preserving margin. Rocket Lab, operating a smaller expendable vehicle, must charge far more per kilogram to cover its full-vehicle cost structure. The ~7x revenue-per-launch gap understates the competitive divergence; the ~11x per-kg gap is the more economically meaningful figure.\n\n### 5. The Specific Disclosure Missing from the SpaceX S-1\n\nTo make this comparison **precise rather than approximate**, the SpaceX S-1 would need to disclose what Rocket Lab\'s 10-K discloses but SpaceX\'s S-1 omits:\n\n**Primary missing disclosure — a directly stated, defined "average revenue per launch" (or "average price per launch") KPI:**\n- Rocket Lab provides a formally defined metric ("average transaction price attributable to launch contract performance obligations") with explicit dollar values ($8.5M / $7.8M / $7.1M) and a companion cost-per-launch metric ($4.8M / $5.7M / $7.0M).\n- SpaceX\'s S-1 **references** the concept ("average price per launch remained relatively flat") but **does not quantify it** and does not define it as a KPI. The figure must be reverse-engineered from disaggregated revenue and launch counts.\n\n**Secondary missing disclosure — a clean mapping of customer launches to revenue sub-lines:**\n- The S-1 discloses total customer launches (43 in 2025) but does **not** split them between Launch Services missions (point-in-time revenue, Falcon 9/Falcon Heavy payload deployment) and Launch & Development missions (over-time revenue, government programs using Falcon 9/Falcon Heavy/Starship/Dragon). Because Launch & Development revenue is recognized over time using cost-to-cost input — not tied 1:1 to a launch event — mixing these into a single customer-launch denominator makes any per-launch calculation inherently imprecise. Rocket Lab avoids this problem by disclosing revenue per launch as a transaction-price metric independent of recognition timing.\n\n**Tertiary missing disclosure — cost per launch:**\n- Rocket Lab discloses cost per launch, enabling a direct gross-margin-per-launch comparison. SpaceX\'s S-1 provides no equivalent, so the margin impact of reusability cannot be quantified from the filing — only inferred from the 95% flight-proven booster rate.\n\nIn short: the SpaceX S-1 provides enough data to construct an **approximate** implied revenue-per-launch proxy (~$57–60M for 2023–2025), but it lacks the **directly disclosed, defined average-revenue-per-launch figure** (and the customer-launch-to-sub-line mapping, and cost-per-launch) that Rocket Lab\'s 10-K provides — which is precisely the disclosure that would convert this directional comparison into a precise one.\n\n---\n\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026)"\n    },\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1819994/000181999426000013/rklb-20251231.htm",\n      "name": "Rocket Lab Corp Form 10-K for fiscal year ended December 31, 2025 (filed February 26, 2026)"\n    }\n  ]\n}'
